msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:80
msgid ""
"Slows down the wheel by applying a braking force. The wheel is only "
"slowed down if it is in contact with a surface. The force you need to "
"apply to adequately slow down your vehicle depends on the "
":ref:`RigidBody.mass <class_RigidBody_property_mass>` of the vehicle. For"
" a vehicle with a mass set to 1000, try a value in the 25 - 30 range for "
"hard braking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:86
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **damping_compression**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:91
msgid "set_damping_compression(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:93
msgid "get_damping_compression()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:96
msgid ""
"The damping applied to the spring when the spring is being compressed. "
"This value should be between 0.0 (no damping) and 1.0. A value of 0.0 "
"means the car will keep bouncing as the spring keeps its energy. A good "
"value for this is around 0.3 for a normal car, 0.5 for a race car."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:102
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **damping_relaxation**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:107
msgid "set_damping_relaxation(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:109
msgid "get_damping_relaxation()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:112
msgid ""
"The damping applied to the spring when relaxing. This value should be "
"between 0.0 (no damping) and 1.0. This value should always be slightly "
"higher than the :ref:`damping_compression "
"<class_VehicleWheel_property_damping_compression>` property. For a "
":ref:`damping_compression "
"<class_VehicleWheel_property_damping_compression>` value of 0.3, try a "
"relaxation value of 0.5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:118
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **engine_force**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:123
msgid "set_engine_force(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:125
msgid "get_engine_force()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:128
msgid ""
"Accelerates the wheel by applying an engine force. The wheel is only "
"speed up if it is in contact with a surface. The :ref:`RigidBody.mass "
"<class_RigidBody_property_mass>` of the vehicle has an effect on the "
"acceleration of the vehicle. For a vehicle with a mass set to 1000, try a"
" value in the 25 - 50 range for acceleration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:130
msgid ""
"**Note:** The simulation does not take the effect of gears into account, "
"you will need to add logic for this if you wish to simulate gears."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:132
msgid "A negative value will result in the wheel reversing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:138
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **steering**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:143
msgid "set_steering(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:145
msgid "get_steering()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:148
msgid ""
"The steering angle for the wheel. Setting this to a non-zero value will "
"result in the vehicle turning when it's moving."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:154
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **suspension_max_force**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:159
msgid "set_suspension_max_force(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:161
msgid "get_suspension_max_force()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:164
msgid ""
"The maximum force the spring can resist. This value should be higher than"
" a quarter of the :ref:`RigidBody.mass <class_RigidBody_property_mass>` "
"of the :ref:`VehicleBody <class_VehicleBody>` or the spring will not "
"carry the weight of the vehicle. Good results are often obtained by a "
"value that is about 3× to 4× this number."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:170
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **suspension_stiffness**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:175
msgid "set_suspension_stiffness(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:177
msgid "get_suspension_stiffness()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:180
msgid ""
"This value defines the stiffness of the suspension. Use a value lower "
"than 50 for an off-road car, a value between 50 and 100 for a race car "
"and try something around 200 for something like a Formula 1 car."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:186
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **suspension_travel**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:191
msgid "set_suspension_travel(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:193
msgid "get_suspension_travel()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:196
msgid ""
"This is the distance the suspension can travel. As Godot units are "
"equivalent to meters, keep this setting relatively low. Try a value "
"between 0.1 and 0.3 depending on the type of car."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:202
msgid ":ref:`bool <class_bool>` **use_as_steering**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:207
msgid "set_use_as_steering(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:209
msgid "is_used_as_steering()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:212
msgid ""
"If ``true``, this wheel will be turned when the car steers. This value is"
" used in conjunction with :ref:`VehicleBody.steering "
"<class_VehicleBody_property_steering>` and ignored if you are using the "
"per-wheel :ref:`steering <class_VehicleWheel_property_steering>` value "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:218
msgid ":ref:`bool <class_bool>` **use_as_traction**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:223
msgid "set_use_as_traction(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:225
msgid "is_used_as_traction()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:228
msgid ""
"If ``true``, this wheel transfers engine force to the ground to propel "
"the vehicle forward. This value is used in conjunction with "
":ref:`VehicleBody.engine_force <class_VehicleBody_property_engine_force>`"
" and ignored if you are using the per-wheel :ref:`engine_force "
"<class_VehicleWheel_property_engine_force>` value instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:234
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **wheel_friction_slip**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:239
msgid "set_friction_slip(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:241
msgid "get_friction_slip()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:244
msgid ""
"This determines how much grip this wheel has. It is combined with the "
"friction setting of the surface the wheel is in contact with. 0.0 means "
"no grip, 1.0 is normal grip. For a drift car setup, try setting the grip "
"of the rear wheels slightly lower than the front wheels, or use a lower "
"value to simulate tire wear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:246
msgid "It's best to set this to 1.0 when starting out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:252
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **wheel_radius**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:257
msgid "set_radius(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:259
msgid "get_radius()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:262
msgid "The radius of the wheel in meters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:268
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **wheel_rest_length**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:273
msgid "set_suspension_rest_length(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:275
msgid "get_suspension_rest_length()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:278
msgid ""
"This is the distance in meters the wheel is lowered from its origin "
"point. Don't set this to 0.0 and move the wheel into position, instead "
"move the origin point of your wheel (the gizmo in Godot) to the position "
"the wheel will take when bottoming out, then use the rest length to move "
"the wheel down to the position it should be in when the car is in rest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:284
msgid ":ref:`float <class_float>` **wheel_roll_influence**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:289
msgid "set_roll_influence(value)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:291
msgid "get_roll_influence()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../docs/classes/class_vehiclewheel.rst:294
msgid ""
"This value affects the roll of your vehicle. If set to 1.0 for all "
"wheels, your vehicle will be prone to rolling over, while a value of 0.0 "
"will resist body roll."
msgstr ""

